message.content:
The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT18 NT68  
   NT68 is a pre-terminal that can produce only t1, t88 or t100.  
   Because the given 25-token string does not contain any of these
   terminals, no split of the string can leave one of them as the
   final (or initial) single token produced by NT68.  
   Hence this branch is impossible.

2. S → NT24 NT54  
   NT24 has exactly the productions  

        NT24 → NT0 NT3            (length ≥ 2)  
        NT24 → 't119' | 't24' | 't141' | 't0'   (length = 1)

   So the prefix produced by NT24 must be either one of the four single
   terminals above, or a two-token sequence whose second token is
   generated by NT3.  
   NT3, however, is a strict pre-terminal with

        NT3 → 't94' | 't23' | 't163'

   None of the tokens t119, t24, t141, t0, t94, t23 or t163 appears as
   the first or second token (indeed, none appears anywhere) in the
   given string, whose first two tokens are t91 t15.  Therefore no
   prefix of the string can be derived from NT24, and this second
   branch is also impossible.

Since neither of the only two possible first steps for S can yield the
given string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

S can expand in only two ways:  
1. S → NT18 NT68  or  2. S → NT24 NT54  

1.  NT68 is a pre-terminal that produces exactly one of the terminals  
   t1, t88 or t100.  
   Whichever split point we choose, the NT68 part must be a contiguous
   suffix of the whole string and must therefore end the string with one of
   those three tokens.  
   The given string ends with t115, so the first alternative is impossible.

2.  For the second alternative we must split the 30-token string so that the
   prefix is generated by NT24 and the remaining suffix by NT54.

   • NT24 can produce either a single token (t119, t24, t141 or t0) or the
     two-token sequence (NT0 NT3).  
     The only workable prefix here is the single token t119, because
     neither NT0 (t73 or t152) nor NT3 (t94 or t23) matches t119.  
     Hence NT24 must generate just the first token t119, leaving the
     29-token suffix to NT54.

   • NT54 has only three binary productions:  
     NT54 → NT42 NT17 | NT35 NT13 | NT20 NT50  

     – NT42 is a pre-terminal for t181, t98 or t48, so if that rule were
       used the suffix would have to start with one of those three tokens.
       It actually starts with t160, so this rule is impossible.  

     – NT35 can begin only with t183, t210, t176 or a token produced by
       NT29 (t73, t9, t109, t104, t42, t132, t224, t127, t10, t130, t48,
       …) — never with t160. Thus the production NT35 NT13 cannot match the
       suffix either.  

     – For NT20 NT50, the left child NT20 can start only with t4, t116,
       t68, t154, t184, t56, t166, t227, t154, t168, t119, t40, t105,
       t150 or t28 (coming from its various possible first symbols), but
       not with t160.  Hence this third rule also cannot derive a string
       whose first token is t160.

   Therefore NT54 cannot generate the 29-token suffix beginning with t160,
   making the second alternative impossible as well.

Since neither of the only two possibilities for S works, the string is not
in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT18 NT68  
   – NT68 is a single terminal (it only produces ‘t1’ or ‘t100’).  
   – Therefore the very last symbol of any sentence derived by this rule must be t1 or t100.  
   – Choosing the only viable possibility for the given string (the final token is t1), the preceding 36 tokens would have to be generated by NT18.  
   – NT18 can either be the single terminal t191 or it must expand as NT18 → NT4 NT12.  
     • NT12 is a single-terminal non-terminal (t49, t91, t3 or t215), so it can cover only the next-to-last token of the string.  
     • Consequently NT4 would have to cover the first 35 tokens and, by its only production NT4 → NT37 NT69, it must finish with whatever NT69 produces.  
     • NT69 is a single terminal, fixed to t93.  
     • The 35th token of the string is t1, not t93.  
   – Hence S → NT18 NT68 cannot yield the given sentence.

2. S → NT24 NT54  
   – Whatever NT24 produces must appear at the very start of the sentence.  
   – NT24 can be one of the terminals {t119, t24, t0, t141} or expand as NT24 → NT0 NT3.  
     • None of the direct terminals matches the first token (t116).  
     • If NT24 → NT0 NT3, the first token must come from NT0.  
       – NT0 can start with the terminal t116 (via NT0 → NT49 NT31 with NT49 → t116).  
       – In that case the second token must be generated by NT31, but NT31 can only be t216 or start with t157, neither of which is the actual second token t183.  
   – Therefore the prefix of the string cannot be produced by NT24, so S → NT24 NT54 is impossible as well.

Since neither of the only two possible derivations for S can match the given string, the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.
